ouse on Main Street."}],"residence":{"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Born in Plymouth in his father's transition year","body":"He was born in Plymouth, Massachusetts on May 29, 1661 — where his father Rev. Samuel Hooker had been preaching for several years. The family moved to Farmington that same year, where his father succeeded his brother-in-law Roger Newton as minister."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"His house stood south of the burial ground","body":"Samuel Hooker II had a fine residence at Farmington, next south of the old burial ground — later known as the Mix house — and ran a store for mercantile business in Hartford. He was one of the first of the Farmington Hookers to move from ministry into trade."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"He married a wealthy sea captain's daughter","body":"In 1687 Samuel Hooker married Mehitabel Hamlin of Middletown, daughter of Capt. Giles Hamlin, a noted and wealthy sea captain and merchant. Hooker kept a store and traded out of Hartford while living at Farmington."}],"cross_connections":[],"career":[{"role":"Merchant","organization":"Farmington / Hartford","notes":"Mercantile business. Store and fine residence at Farmington."}],"education":[{"degree":"B.A.","notes":"B.A. Harvard; later a fellow of the college. (Julius Gay, Farmington Historical Pamphlets)","school_name":"Harvard College","institution_id":"INST002"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Samuel Hooker II","first_name":"Samuel","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":[],"suffix":"II","bio_blurb":"Farmington storekeeper and Hartford merchant"},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002","relationship":"alumnus"}],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM003","plot_notes":"Ancient Burying Ground, Hartford CT. SOURCE: FindAGrave."},"sl